1
00:00:00,892 --> 00:00:18,225
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambhodassa

2
00:00:18,204 --> 00:00:32,097
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma-sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:33,005 --> 00:00:38,093
So I thought this evening we'd have a look at the contemplation of the body.

4
00:00:38,292 --> 00:00:53,475
Now, the Buddha actually offers us quite a few ways of doing it, but I'm going to go for the asubha contemplations, which translates as the repulsive or the unpleasant parts of the body.

5
00:00:54,676 --> 00:00:56,058
It's going to be really wonderful.

6
00:00:57,136 --> 00:01:02,225
So, first of all, we have to undermine.

7
00:01:02,265 --> 00:01:09,477
Well, the purpose of the exercise is to undermine our wrong relationship to the body, whereby we own it.

8
00:01:09,736 --> 00:01:12,581
It's something that we have or we are.

9
00:01:12,742 --> 00:01:15,987
So we'll say things like, you know, I have a headache.

10
00:01:15,968 --> 00:01:17,469
I've got weak knees.

11
00:01:18,331 --> 00:01:21,335
But then, of course, you will say, I am ill, right?

12
00:01:22,057 --> 00:01:28,906
So there's this dual relationship we have, both of which happen to be wrong and lead us to suffering.

13
00:01:29,929 --> 00:01:32,031
So that's the purpose of the exercise.

14
00:01:32,832 --> 00:01:35,736
There are other purposes, but I'll mention them towards the end.

15
00:01:37,319 --> 00:01:45,671
Now, it's good to begin such an exercise by...

16
00:01:46,546 --> 00:01:49,811
reminding ourselves how precious this life is.

17
00:01:51,373 --> 00:02:08,138
So here we experience this joy and woe, just like animals do, but we have this developed intelligence, this intuitive intelligence, which has come, according to Buddhism, through countless births.

18
00:02:09,239 --> 00:02:14,426
And because of that, we're in this place and we're able to make our way out of suffering.

19
00:02:15,233 --> 00:02:20,246
There are other realms which you can also think of as mental states, the hell realm.

20
00:02:20,325 --> 00:02:26,341
So people who are, for instance, deeply depressed or in one of the more severe mental illnesses.

21
00:02:27,263 --> 00:02:29,849
There's the animal realm where people get drunk.

22
00:02:31,400 --> 00:02:40,271
There's the insatiable hungry ghost realm, people chasing money all the time.

23
00:02:41,593 --> 00:02:42,756
There's the human, of course.

24
00:02:42,816 --> 00:02:44,457
And then there's these angry gods.

25
00:02:44,518 --> 00:02:45,318
So we've got lots.

26
00:02:45,438 --> 00:02:51,347
Unfortunately, we've got lots of experience of that at the moment with Ukraine and Gaza and Sudan.

27
00:02:52,188 --> 00:02:55,432
And finally, there are the happy gods, all those wonderful things.

28
00:02:55,413 --> 00:02:59,456
multi-billionaires who are sitting on their yachts.

29
00:02:59,477 --> 00:03:09,006
So those areas, there's not much joy, there's not much hope rather of finding liberation because nothing's pushing them.

30
00:03:09,026 --> 00:03:14,950
It's this lovely place of being happy and unhappy.

31
00:03:15,532 --> 00:03:23,359
And it's an inability to maintain that happiness that leads us to seek the end of it all.

32
00:03:24,020 --> 00:03:24,340
Okay.

33
00:03:29,212 --> 00:03:31,856
So obviously we can't be here without a body.

34
00:03:32,177 --> 00:03:32,838
That's number one.

35
00:03:33,680 --> 00:03:36,384
It's through the senses that we experience the world.

36
00:03:36,965 --> 00:03:39,229
Everything we come to know has come through the senses.

37
00:03:40,450 --> 00:03:43,536
Well, not everything, but virtually everything has come through the senses.

38
00:03:44,897 --> 00:03:48,844
It's through the body we relate, we communicate, we express ourselves.

39
00:03:49,906 --> 00:03:52,950
Through the body we work, we do things, we help others.

40
00:03:53,992 --> 00:03:56,537
In other words, creating good karma.

41
00:03:56,804 --> 00:04:06,137
And in virtually every meditation technique, the body is always central to the process.

42
00:04:08,319 --> 00:04:20,937
So before we go into these asubha contemplations, these disgusting contemplations, it's always good to apologize to the body for any harm we've done it.

43
00:04:21,322 --> 00:04:26,630
And I've got this little verse, which you can repeat after me.

44
00:04:27,572 --> 00:04:35,803
And that gives you a sort of starting point for this sort of contemplation.

45
00:04:36,403 --> 00:04:36,745
Okay.

46
00:04:38,427 --> 00:04:40,911
So just closing your eyes for a moment.

47
00:04:43,735 --> 00:04:48,781
Whatever harm I have done to you in thought, word and deed.

48
00:04:53,723 --> 00:04:57,850
By way of greed, hatred and delusion?

49
00:05:03,560 --> 00:05:06,125
Intentionally or unintentionally?

50
00:05:13,016 --> 00:05:15,040
I'm heartily sorry for it.

51
00:05:21,095 --> 00:05:26,083
and I determine from this day on to treat you with due care and respect.

52
00:05:31,851 --> 00:05:35,158
Now this puts us into a good relationship with the body.

53
00:05:36,740 --> 00:05:41,668
Now, this is what the Buddha tells us in the Dhammapada,

54
00:05:41,850 --> 00:05:57,045
having understood that this body is like foam, having realized its mirage-like nature, having cut off Mara's flower-tipped arrows, one should make himself invisible to the king of death.

55
00:05:57,807 --> 00:06:07,757
So these flower-tipped arrows are these little pushes we get, you know, just for that extra bit of cake and do this and do that, see, led by greed.

56
00:06:09,204 --> 00:06:21,264
And then he says, knowing that this body is like foam, fully awake to the mirage-like nature, cutting off mara's flowers, one goes unseen by the king of death.

57
00:06:22,086 --> 00:06:34,166
In other words, once we've cut out our wrong relationship with the world, we can presume that dying will no longer be something to be feared.

58
00:06:35,665 --> 00:06:42,492
So I'm taking this exercise from a discourse, the Giramananda Sutta.

59
00:06:42,512 --> 00:06:45,454
It's about Giramananda.

60
00:06:46,415 --> 00:06:50,240
He's sick and Ananda's gone to the Buddha and says, what can we do for him?

61
00:06:50,360 --> 00:06:52,923
So he says, well, give him these 10 contemplations.

62
00:06:53,543 --> 00:07:03,213
So I won't go through the 10 contemplations, but two of them are the unpleasantness of the body and then it's drawbacks.

63
00:07:03,372 --> 00:07:05,115
So now the idea is,

64
00:07:05,533 --> 00:07:23,952
And as I read through these different parts of the body, and you're sitting in meditation, as you contact them through your imagination and through your memory, through your nose, through your eyes, et cetera, just catch your relationship, right?

65
00:07:23,973 --> 00:07:31,221
Most of them I think you'll find fairly neutral, but some you'll have some contact.

66
00:07:33,074 --> 00:07:36,538
some relationship of disgust, right?

67
00:07:37,478 --> 00:07:38,560
At some level or other.

68
00:07:39,040 --> 00:07:43,547
So it's really getting in touch with that and recognizing that it's not necessary, right?

69
00:07:43,567 --> 00:07:47,752
We don't have to feel disgusted with the body because the body is just what it is.

70
00:07:49,413 --> 00:08:00,387
And then after that, we'll just run through all these wonderful things, these horrible things that can happen to the body as a reminder that we must continue our meditation with vigor.

71
00:08:01,529 --> 00:08:01,949
Okay.

72
00:08:03,230 --> 00:08:12,041
So if you just find yourself in a quiet place for a moment, and I shall give you the instructions from the Buddha.

73
00:08:33,722 --> 00:08:41,639
So examining our body from the soles of the feet and down from the tips of the hair.

74
00:08:45,988 --> 00:08:46,970
We'll just go down.

75
00:08:47,049 --> 00:08:48,153
We won't come up again.

76
00:08:49,535 --> 00:08:55,106
So just starting at the top there, you see, just the hair that's on the body.

77
00:09:04,672 --> 00:09:31,557
And then there's nails, teeth, the skin, the muscles, the sinews,

78
00:09:38,287 --> 00:10:02,269
the bones, the bone marrow, the kidneys, the heart,

79
00:10:09,471 --> 00:10:35,918
the liver, the spleen, the lungs, the intestines,

80
00:10:42,951 --> 00:11:07,339
the bowels, the undigested food, the bile, the pus,

81
00:11:13,511 --> 00:11:39,232
the fat, the tears, the blood, saliva,

82
00:11:45,270 --> 00:12:02,789
snot, feces, stools, and urine.

83
00:12:12,034 --> 00:12:27,269
So now, if you go back to the one where there was some sense of disgust, just bring it back to mind and just get in touch with that relationship.

84
00:12:27,288 --> 00:12:29,553
What does disgust really feel like?

85
00:12:48,028 --> 00:12:50,211
And then ask yourself, is it necessary?

86
00:13:04,394 --> 00:13:08,561
Can we change our relationship to it by seeing it differently?

87
00:13:09,863 --> 00:13:13,428
Function, product,

88
00:13:15,417 --> 00:13:18,000
biologically, scientifically.

89
00:13:40,081 --> 00:13:44,225
So in this way, we come to accept the body just as it is.

90
00:13:44,576 --> 00:13:48,244
But then the Buddha reminds us of all the things that can go wrong.

91
00:13:49,686 --> 00:13:56,357
And this is meant to, of course, give us that samvega, that sense of urgency to continue our practice.

92
00:14:01,827 --> 00:14:05,455
This body has much suffering and many drawbacks.

93
00:14:06,110 --> 00:14:11,258
But this body is beset with many kinds of affliction, such as the following.

94
00:14:12,259 --> 00:14:23,375
Diseases of the eye, the inner ear, the nose, the tongue, the body, the head, the outer ear, the mouth, the teeth and lips.

95
00:14:24,875 --> 00:14:54,881
There's the cough and asthma, catarrh, inflammation, fever, stomachache, fainting, dysentery, gastric pain, cholera, leprosy, boils, eczema, tuberculosis, epilepsy, herpes, itch, scabs, smallpox, scabies,

96
00:14:55,148 --> 00:15:04,178
Hemorrhages, diabetes, piles, pimples, ulcers and cancer.

97
00:15:06,120 --> 00:15:12,989
Afflictions stemming from disorders of the bile, phlegm, wind or their conjunction.

98
00:15:14,270 --> 00:15:22,640
Afflictions caused by changing weather, by not taking care of ourselves, by overexertion.

99
00:15:22,773 --> 00:15:33,033
or as a result of past deeds, cold, heat, hunger, thirst, defecation and urination.

100
00:15:34,817 --> 00:15:40,849
And so he asks us to meditate, observing the drawbacks of this body.

101
00:15:44,136 --> 00:15:48,881
So again, it's just recognizing that the body is subject to disease.

102
00:15:50,082 --> 00:15:51,783
It's not gone beyond disease.

103
00:15:52,485 --> 00:15:54,267
It is of a nature to fall in.

104
00:15:56,469 --> 00:16:07,700
This is meant to help us to begin to see the body in a different way, to take care of it, but not to be enthralled by it.

105
00:16:12,705 --> 00:16:13,164
Now,

106
00:16:15,337 --> 00:16:18,380
By the way, on that list, I added cancer.

107
00:16:18,741 --> 00:16:21,985
I don't know whether they had cancer or not in those days.

108
00:16:22,625 --> 00:16:23,447
It's not listed.

109
00:16:25,369 --> 00:16:43,489
Anyway, what happened was that the Buddha did give this teaching about the unattractiveness of the body in praise of perceiving the unattractiveness of the body and in praise of development of the perception of the unattractiveness of the body.

110
00:16:44,937 --> 00:16:47,921
And he went off then for seclusion for half a month.

111
00:16:50,082 --> 00:16:56,191
And when he came out, he said to Ananda, why does the Sangha of monks seem so depleted?

112
00:16:58,212 --> 00:17:04,621
Because Lord, the Blessed One, with many lines of reasoning, gave monks the talk of unattractiveness.

113
00:17:08,625 --> 00:17:13,070
Spoke in praise of the development of the perception of unattractiveness.

114
00:17:14,401 --> 00:17:20,810
The monk's thinking, the Blessed One with many lines of reasoning, has given a talk on unattractiveness.

115
00:17:21,833 --> 00:17:28,722
They remained committed to the development of the perception of unattractiveness in many modes and manners.

116
00:17:29,944 --> 00:17:37,557
And they, ashamed, repelled or disgusted with the body, sought for an assassin.

117
00:17:37,991 --> 00:17:41,578
In one day, 10 monks took the knife.

118
00:17:42,441 --> 00:17:45,807
In one day, 20 monks took the knife.

119
00:17:45,827 --> 00:17:48,794
In one day, 30 monks took the knife.

120
00:17:49,654 --> 00:17:58,953
It would be good, Lord, if the Blessed One would explain another method so that this sangha of monks might be established in understanding.

121
00:17:59,457 --> 00:18:14,492
Now, I can't imagine what the Buddha must have felt when he found out that this contemplation he'd given to his monks had driven them to suicide and seemingly to monks helping people to commit suicide.

122
00:18:15,233 --> 00:18:27,928
In fact, it was on this occasion that he declared the first harajika, which is a rule for the monks, which if you break it, you lose your ordination.

123
00:18:28,448 --> 00:18:37,096
So anything to do with killing another person is not allowed.

124
00:18:38,737 --> 00:18:45,624
So he gave them the contemplation of jhana to produce beautiful mental states.

125
00:18:46,163 --> 00:18:51,308
Well, of course, you need time to do that sort of practice.

126
00:18:52,750 --> 00:18:57,914
So another way of doing it is by offering gratitude to the body.

127
00:19:00,545 --> 00:19:16,150
But before we do that, let me just remind you of the purpose of this exercise is to encourage detachment from the body and to especially undermine that relationship of identity.

128
00:19:17,893 --> 00:19:23,261
It can sometimes be used, especially in the monastic orders, to cool sexual impulses.

129
00:19:24,051 --> 00:19:38,548
So the idea is that when some erotic idea comes to mind, you then remind yourself that this body is also not particularly erotic, and this should allow the sexual energy to die away.

130
00:19:38,567 --> 00:19:51,882
If, of course, a person were simply to continue developing that disgust of the body, then they would lose their sexual impulse completely.

131
00:19:56,282 --> 00:20:03,074
And it's to undermine society's emphasis on physical beauty and attractiveness.

132
00:20:03,654 --> 00:20:03,974
Okay.

133
00:20:08,041 --> 00:20:17,016
So what I'm going to do is ask you to then go through the body in the same way from the top of the head all the way down to the toes.

134
00:20:17,517 --> 00:20:23,926
And as you go down and you visualize that part of the body, just say thank you.

135
00:20:24,582 --> 00:20:28,849
Thank you for, for instance, give it a purpose if you want.

136
00:20:29,551 --> 00:20:34,080
So the skin, thank you for the protection you give this body.

137
00:20:35,923 --> 00:20:38,229
So just take your time going down.

138
00:20:38,388 --> 00:20:42,257
And then when you finish that, just go into the meditation.

139
00:20:43,659 --> 00:20:47,046
Okay, so it's offering gratitude to the body.

140
00:20:49,625 --> 00:20:55,718
And I think you'll find that all the cells jump up and down with great joy.

141
00:20:55,758 --> 00:21:02,672
Finally, their work is being appreciated.

142
00:21:02,692 --> 00:21:10,147
So if we sit in silence and then just begin going down, saying thank you to all the different parts of the body.

